 SECTION 1
CIA Triad
Confidentiality = Keep data private.
Integrity = Keep data accurate.
Availability = Keep systems accessible.

Authentication - Verifying who a user is.
Examples: Password - Fingerprint - MFA 

Authorization - Determines what a user can access.

Accounting - Tracks user activity.

Malware = Malicious software.
Types= Virus - Worm - Trojan - Ransomware - Spyware


Phishing = Fake messages used to steal information.
Defense: Verify sender - Avoid suspicious links - 

Social Engineering = Tricking people into giving information.

Examples: Phishing - Tailgating - Impersonation






SECTION 2 

Firewall = Blocks unwanted network traffic.

Antivirus = Detects and removes malware.

VPN = Encrypts internet traffic.

Encryption = Turns readable data into unreadable data.
Purpose:Protect sensitive information

Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA) = Uses two or more login methods.
Example:Password + Phone Code

Risk = Threat × Vulnerability

Vulnerability = A weakness in a system.

Threat = Anything that could cause harm.

Patch Management = Regularly updating software to fix vulnerabilities.

Principle of Least Privilege = Users should only have access to what they need.

Defense in Depth = Use multiple layers of security.
Example: - Password - MFA - Firewall - Antivirus - Incident Response Steps - Prepare - Detect - Contain - Eradicate - Recover - Review
